00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:20.440
So let's imagine we have two data frames.

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:24.840
We have DFA and DFB.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:32.679
You could define in Python saying that DFA's data is DFB.data, and then you could find,

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:38.359
like, define on B that its data comes from DFA, and so they would depend on each other.

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:43.000
No input would actually come in, and, you know, your computer explodes or something.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.799
I don't know.

00:09:44.799 --> 00:09:48.640
But you need something to where, like, you have your original data set here.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:53.599
You then come in to A. You then go to B, and then you can go on to C and D and whatnot,

00:09:53.599 --> 00:09:56.599
but just don't have it loop back.

00:09:56.599 --> 00:10:00.719
Thank you.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:07.679
So I see there's an anonymous question that came in very early into the demo, and it was,

00:10:07.679 --> 00:10:13.840
why is this not DT for Python, and can you compare and contrast editable tables in R

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:16.400
versus editable tables in Python?

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:20.400
Is there a reason to reconsider R for this?

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:24.400
Darren, you had...

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:26.400
I'll take...

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:29.400
Yeah, I'll take go.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:34.080
DT is a wonderful package.

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:39.960
It was the best on the block 10 years ago when we did it, and there's been a lot of

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:44.440
advancements in the JavaScript world in the recent years, and so we're trying to leverage

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:50.000
that, you know, using TanStack underneath the hood so that things are as fast as possible

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.280
when rendering.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:56.679
So we, you know, there's some engineering design changes that needed to happen, and so

00:10:56.679 --> 00:10:59.760
we can't just reskin it under Python.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:05.239
There is packages like ITables, I believe, in Python that is a wrapper around DT, so

00:11:05.239 --> 00:11:06.840
there are ways to do it.

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:10.599
There are some Shiny widgets, I can't remember, that possibly work in...

00:11:10.599 --> 00:11:15.760
Or not Shiny widgets, IPy widgets that work within Jupyter Notebooks, but the reactive

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:21.479
model within Shiny is really backwards when you're using IPy widgets with Shiny, just

00:11:21.479 --> 00:11:27.000
because IPy widgets pushes you information versus you reacting to that change.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.559
I know it's a subtle thing verbally, but in practice, it feels really wonky within the

00:11:32.559 --> 00:11:34.679
Shiny world.

00:11:34.679 --> 00:11:37.479
So we just needed to catch up to the R world.

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:44.760
I mean, we've had 10 years of experience in the R side, but my usual answer of like, should

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:47.760
I use Python or R?

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:54.840
My generic response is usually whatever you're fastest at producing the desired output, you

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:57.239
should use that.

00:11:57.239 --> 00:12:02.159
Maybe there's a better tool over here or over there, but if you're most comfortable like

00:12:02.159 --> 00:12:05.039
doing your data analysis in R, you should stay there.

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:10.559
If you require a certain feature, you know, maybe you switch to Python.

00:12:10.559 --> 00:12:13.400
Thank you.

00:12:13.799 --> 00:12:18.640
It probably is a good time to address this question as well.

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:23.400
I know, Garrett, you briefly covered a way to do this with R in the beginning of the

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:24.400
