00:13:00.559 --> 00:13:02.359
to share with everybody here as well.

00:13:02.359 --> 00:13:03.359
I do.

00:13:03.359 --> 00:13:06.359
I'll get it for you just in case.

00:13:06.919 --> 00:13:09.919
Perfect.

00:13:09.919 --> 00:13:12.119
Let me go double check over on Slido.

00:13:12.119 --> 00:13:13.119
Oh, okay.

00:13:13.119 --> 00:13:17.280
I see Kelsey asked a question over there.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:23.919
And it was, any pitfalls to watch for if we use this type of app for multiple users editing

00:13:23.919 --> 00:13:24.919
a data table?

00:13:24.919 --> 00:13:29.919
We would like to record when they make changes and revert changes.

00:13:33.919 --> 00:13:34.919
Yes.

00:13:35.479 --> 00:13:38.119
I'll take this one.

00:13:38.119 --> 00:13:40.479
So this, there are a lot of pitfalls.

00:13:40.479 --> 00:13:48.039
I mean, we could have things like when you save to the actual database, I would say transaction

00:13:48.039 --> 00:13:56.280
would say, and if Garrett and I were doing that at the same time, then one of us would

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:03.479
win and the other one would get stomped over, and that's not good for a database transaction.

00:14:04.039 --> 00:14:08.520
I explicitly did not try to make any forced design decisions.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:15.239
So there's the, as Garrett mentioned earlier, the set patch function where you can receive

00:14:15.239 --> 00:14:21.000
an edit from someone, and then it's now your responsibility as the app author to handle

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:22.000
that.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.039
Maybe you're just writing to a local CSV file and it doesn't matter.

00:14:25.039 --> 00:14:31.080
Maybe you're ignoring it completely or you're all sharing the same database connection.

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:40.880
So I would have to default to say like, please leverage your database's ability to perform

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:43.479
transactions and put a lock on the system.

00:14:43.479 --> 00:14:50.679
Yes, that may deter editing, but at least you'll still be able to.

00:14:54.679 --> 00:14:55.679
Thank you.

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:04.080
I see one other question from Bill, which was, one second, can you embed an Excel spreadsheet

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:07.679
in this type of workflow using a Python or R package?

00:15:12.679 --> 00:15:21.559
I'm personally not aware of one, but I think what this is doing is bringing us a step closer

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:27.280
to making the table that is in Shiny function like an Excel spreadsheet.

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:32.520
And then here I've downloaded to CSV.

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:35.919
I don't use spreadsheets that much, but I assume it'd be very easy if I had a package

00:15:35.919 --> 00:15:39.400
that could export a data frame as an Excel spreadsheet, and then you could just pick

00:15:39.400 --> 00:15:43.599
it back up in Excel outside of Shiny.

00:15:43.599 --> 00:15:50.880
I know I've done that before, actually, where you can add a button to the top where the

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:55.080
end user can just download the Excel version of the table.

00:15:55.080 --> 00:16:03.559
I'm trying to remember where documentation for that would be.

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:09.520
So here we're relying on Pandas's to CSV method to take that data frame and put in a CSV format.

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:13.239
And then the download button will take whatever we have and pass it through to the user.

00:16:13.239 --> 00:16:15.960
So we just need to get into the Excel format.

00:16:16.039 --> 00:16:21.840
I feel silly that I can't say with certainty whether there's a to Excel method from Pandas.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.400
It seems like there would be, but I just don't know.

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:30.799
Maybe someone in the chat knows too, if you want to jump in.

00:16:30.799 --> 00:16:33.039
Barrett, anything to add?

00:16:33.039 --> 00:16:40.320
From my knowledge, I'm interpreting Excel spreadsheets as formula support.

00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:46.599
And as far as I know, any editable data frames do not have formula support by default.

00:16:46.599 --> 00:16:58.080
There is the R package of R hands-on table, I believe, and it looks like a spreadsheet,

00:16:58.080 --> 00:16:59.080
but that's about it.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:07.439
It's very nice editing view, similar to DT, or a little bit prettier than DT, but the

00:17:07.439 --> 00:17:09.640
formula support isn't there.

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:18.520
The door has been opened in the Python side for PyShiny, Shine for Python, that if you

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:23.199
edit a cell, we can actually edit more cells as a reaction to that.

00:17:23.199 --> 00:17:28.479
So if you change the value for one cell, we can change the value for multiple cells, which

00:17:28.479 --> 00:17:32.199
I think is really neat, but that is not automatically handled.

00:17:32.199 --> 00:17:37.000
I'm just kind of putting it out there to see if anyone starts to leverage it with formulas.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:45.880
I see Talon shared an example in the chat as well.

